# llama-router

An Ollama router that aggregates multiple Ollama backends behind a single API.

## Architecture

- Built with FastAPI serving both the dashboard and API
- Dashboard uses server-side rendered Jinja2 templates with Bootstrap styling
- Dashboard on port 80 for management and monitoring, shows visual representation of all providers with status, models, and performance data
- Ollama-compatible API on port 11434 (standard Ollama port)
- When a new backend is configured, the router queries it for available models and capabilities, and caches that information
- Authentication is handled by an external reverse proxy; the app itself does not implement auth

## Ollama API

- Not a full pass-through proxy — supports a focused subset of the Ollama API
- Supported use cases: running LLMs, embedding/encoding models
- Key endpoints: `/api/chat`, `/api/embeddings`, `/api/pull`, `/api/tags`, and introspection endpoints
- Does not support `/api/generate` at this time
- Aggregates model lists across all providers for `/api/tags`

## Providers

- Backends are added, removed, and configured through the web dashboard
- Tracks all available Ollama backend providers and their current status (idle, busy, offline)
- Tracks which providers are currently in use and serving requests
- Periodically health-checks providers to detect when they go offline or come back online
- Discovers and records what models each provider has, along with hardware/software capabilities
- Can automatically benchmark providers, measuring startup time and tokens-per-second performance
- Stores benchmark results persistently so performance data survives restarts

## Routing

- When multiple providers have the same model, route to the least-busy, most-capable provider
- Use benchmark data (tokens/sec, startup time) to rank provider capability
- Fall back gracefully when preferred provider is unavailable

## General Conventions

- Use Python 3.11+
- Prefer type hints on all function signatures
- Use `pyproject.toml` for project metadata and dependencies
- Use virtual environments for dependency isolation
- Write docstrings for public modules, classes, and functions
- Keep functions focused and under ~50 lines
- Prefer composition over inheritance

## Lint

- Use black to lint the code
- Keep code passing lint

## Docker

- Provide an example compose file for users
- Provide a compose file for doing tests and lint during development

## GitHub

- GitHub workflow should run tests and linting, then build and push a Docker image to GHCR

